Hey there,
Since your test code doesn't seem to call any initialize, or similar method
in the setup, would it be fair to say that your source code does all of its
event binding as soon as the source file is loaded?
If so, I think what you're seeing is that when you call 'live', jQuery
binds the event to 'document' element which does exist on the page when
that file is loaded. On the other hand, when you are using 'on', the
'#deleteAllDialog' element does not exist when the source file is loaded,
as all source files are loaded before spec files are loaded/executed.
Because that element doesn't exist, events can't be bound to it. If you
wanted to replicate "live" behavior with "on", you would need to do
something like $(document).on("click", "#cancelDeleteAll",...). A better
solution, however, might be to continue using "on" the way you have and
refactor to make the code more testable; for example, by giving the
implementation an initialize function that you can call in test after the
fixture DOM is ready and then that function can do the event binding.
Does that help?
