Hi @marcagas, is this jQuery's fadeOut? If so, it takes a completion handler as the second argument, which you can pass the async completion handler for. Here's an example:
// implementation
function fadeOutElem(callback) {
  $('.elem').fadeOut(300, callback);
}

// test
it("fades out the element", function(done) {
  fadeOutElem(done);
});
If the implementation can't find the '.elem' or for some other reason the callback isn't executed, the 'done' that is threaded through won't be called and you'll get a properly failing spec.
In case it's not possible to thread the callback through, or maybe you're not using something that gives a callback hook for fadeOut(), then you could do something like the following:
it("fades out the element", function(done) {
  fadeOutElem();
  setTimeout(300, function() {
    expect($(".elem").css('display').toEqual('none');
    done();
  });
});
There's also the stubbing approach (again assuming jQuery), where you should be able to do something like the following:
it("fades out the element", function() {
  spyOn($.fn, 'fadeOut');
  fadeOutElem();
  expect($.fn.fadeOut).toHaveBeenCalled();
});
As you mentioned you could probably do something with the Jasmine clock since jQuery might be using setTimeout to do the fading. So something like the following might work:
jasmine.clock().install(); // might even need to be before jQuery is loaded since it could be closing over setTimeout, etc.
it("fades out the element", function() {
  fadeOutElem();
  jasmine.clock().tick(300);
  expect($(".elem").css('display').toEqual('none');
});
The clock seems like a harder way to test this, but those are all the options I can think of!

