I would like to share my solution / hack which is in my opinion could very well be built-in, with no additional complexity to existing code. Evidence is given by this code:
I am running jasmine from jspm command line:

npx jspm run spec/runner

then in my file spec/runner.ts I have first, the jasmine import and configuration for who ever is looking for a complete working example, followed by an override of the it function from the jasmine core, and finally the bootstrapping of the jasmine runner jasmine.execute().
import Jasmine = require("jasmine")
jasmine.config({
    "spec_dir": "spec",
    "spec_files": [
        "**/*[sS]pec.js"
    ],
    "helpers": [
        "helpers/**/*.js"
    ],
    "stopSpecOnExpectationFailure": false,
    "random": true
});
let assertAsync = (assertion?: (done?: DoneFn) => void | { then: Function }) => {
    return (done?: DoneFn) => {
        let result = assertion(done);
        if (result && typeof result.then === "function")
            result.then(done, done.fail);
        else
            done();
    }
};

global['it'] =
(jasmineIt => (expectation: string, assertion?: (done: DoneFn) => void, timeout?: number) => jasmineIt(expectation,
    assertAsync(assertion),
    timeout))(it);

// require statements will be resolved by jspm / systemjs. refer to jspm.io to find more info
require("./specs/myAsyncSpec");

jasmine.execute();


And now in my specs i can write code supporting promises / async / await
describe("manifest", () => {
    it("icons should exists",
        async () => {
            await new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
                resolve();
            });
        });
});

