@brutalcrozt This isn't a problem with Jasmine - https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Operators/this
thisis a reserved word that is scoped within a function, so each function declaration would need to pass the this from the it/beforeEach/etc. block that Jasmine sets up into the inner functions. There are a few ways to accomplish this:
Manually bind your function using Function.prototype.bind:
it('uses Function.prototype.bind', function() {
 // this = the this that Jasmine bound to the it function
  expect(function() { 
    // this = the this that was bound to the outer function (the one Jasmine supplied)
  }.bind(this)).toThrow(...)
});

Use the ES6 Arrow function (fat arrow) syntax, which accomplishes the same behavior of function(){}.bind(this) with a shorthand syntax (https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Functions/Arrow_functions)
it('uses ES6 Arrow functions', function() {
  // this = the this that Jasmine bound to the it function
  expect(function() => {
    // this = the this that was bound to the outer function (the one Jasmine supplied)
  }).toThrow(...);
});

Refer to the Jasmine-supplied this in the it function:
it('uses closures', function() {
  var self = this;
  expect(function() {
  // self is captured in the closure, so you can refer to self.whatever inside the inner function
  }).toThrow(...);
});

Depending on what JS standard was available to me, I'd choose ES6 Arrow func > Function.prototype.bind > var self = this.
If you have other questions about usage, please send them to the mailing list as github issues are intended to be used for feature requests and issues.

