comments_data.contents:
Hello @viniciusdacal,
I believe it's just working as intended.
As parameters of a function in Javascript, objects are passed by 'copy of it's reference', thus any change you perform to the object itself will be effective.
function replace(ref) {
    ref = {};           // this code does _not_ affect the object passed
}
function update(ref) {
    ref.key = 'newvalue';  // this code _does_ affect the _contents_ of the object
}
var a = { key: 'value' };
replace(a);  // a still has its original value - it's unmodified
update(a);   // the _contents_ of 'a' are changed

Not all objects are trivially copyable, and some aren't copyable at all. Consider an object that's part of a cyclical graph, like a tree whose nodes link to both parents and children. Or an object that references something non-copyable like one of the builtin browser globals. It would be difficult to test code that uses objects like that if toHaveBeenCalledWith tried to copy its argument.
@viniciusdacal, in the example you gave you could just pass the same object reference to both functions:
var account = {name: 'Kakaroto account'};
accountService.create(account);
expect(accountService.create).toHaveBeenCalledWith(account);
Of course a real test would be more involved than that, and maybe the test can't directly access the object that will be passed to createAccount. In that case you could use the tracking properties of the spy to inspect the argument, like this (untested, beware of errors):
triggerAccountCreationSomehow();
expect(accountService.create).toHaveBeenCalled();
expect(accountService.create.calls.argsFor(0)[0].name).toEqual('Kakaroto account')

