It's not a bug, you're doing an async operation so Jasmine doesn't have a way to know when your test is done.
There's some documentation of async tests here: http://jasmine.github.io/edge/introduction.html#section-Asynchronous_Support
You need to ask for the done callback in the it's function, something like this:
it('does something async', function(done) {
  doSomethingAsync().then(function() {
    expect('foo').toEqual('foo');
    done();
  }, function(e) {
    done.fail('The promise rejected because of ' + e.message);
  });
});

