comments_data.contents:
The second expect never fails because it never runs: person.name throws a TypeError as soon as it's run, and it's not possible to continue after that because of the javascript engine.
You could wrap the second and third expect in try/catch, one for both or one each, and manually deal with the caught errors, then fail with Jasmine's fail().
var erred = false;
var thing = getObjectOrNull();

expect(thing).not.toBeNull();

try {
    expect(thing.a).toBe('a');
} catch (error) {
    erred = true;
    console.error(error);
}

try {
    expect(thing.b).toBe('b');
} catch (error) {
    erred = true;
    console.error(error);
}

if (erred) {
    fail('Errors thrown');
} else {
    done();
}
Or, more succinctly:
var erred = false;
var thing = getObjectOrNull();

expect(thing).not.toBeNull();

if (typeof thing === 'object') {
    expect(thing.a).toBe('a');
    expect(thing.b).toBe('b');
} else {
    fail('thing is not object');
}
As a side note, you don't need done for synchronous tests, so you can remove it from the spec's function arguments and the spec will end when the function ends.

