We are experiencing this, too, with Jasmine 2.5.2. It happens with every test case that is executed asynchronously, such as via a task or microtask (ES "Job"). The simplest test case to reproduce this, would be via setTimeout() task:
it('...', done => {
  setTimeout(() => {
    fail('...');
  }, 0);
});
It fails with:
Error: Timeout - Async callback was not invoked within timeout specified by jasmine.DEFAULT_TIMEOUT_INTERVAL.

Our real usecase is more sophisticated with a microtask (via a Promise), which can be summarized to:
it('...', done => {
  thePromise().then(result => {
    done(); // <- will not reach here because promise throws
  }).catch(err => {
    fail(); // <- this will be called and should fail the test, but doesn't.
  });
});
Using done() in asynchronous tests however works. So done() must be doing something more than fail() with regards to notifying test completion.
That is, a quick workaround for the above test case would be:
it('...', done => {
  thePromise().then(result => {
    done(); // <- will not reach here because promise throws
  }).catch(err => {
    fail(); // <- this will be called and should fail the test, but doesn't.
    done(); // <- completes the test with a fail, because of the fail() call
  });
});

