I've used something like this...
describe('outer', () => {
  function init (options) {
    // Common init behavior here...
    if (options.opt1) {
      // Different behavior depending on options.
    } else {
      // Different behavior depending on options.
    }
  };
  describe('inner 1', () => {
    beforeEach(() => {
      init({ opt1: true, opt2: false });
    });
    it('test 1', () => {
    });
    it('test 2', () => {
    });
  });
  describe('inner 2', () => {
    beforeEach(() => {
      init({ opt1: false, opt2: true });
    });
    it('test 1', () => {
    });
    it('test 2', () => {
    });
  });
});
The idea is to use a common init() function which has options to control its behavior. You can then have different nested describe blocks which call init() inside their beforeEach(), but using different options. I pulled this example based on something I'd done in Jest, but hopefully it's also applicable to Jasmine.

