comments_data.contents:
We've had a few requests for this feature. The biggest problem is that async is "contagious" -- if a function calls an async function and wants to do anything with the result, it has to be async itself. So if matchers are async, then all specs have to be async as well. Which means that implementing this feature would break the majority of Jasmine specs.
The other problem is that the feature would be difficult to use correctly. In order for Jasmine to associate the failure with the spec that causes it, it would be necessary to await the expect call so that the spec doesn't finish until after the matcher is evaluated:
it('throws an error on invalid argument', async () => {
  await expect(async () => {
    await methodBeingTested(invalidArgument);
  }).toThrow(ExpectedError);
})

That would be really easy to forget, in which case Jasmine would associate the failure with the wrong spec or no spec at all. We already see that problem when people call done at the wrong time, and it can be incredibly time-consuming to debug.
So, to sum up: I recognize the value of this feature, but it would require users to rewrite most existing specs and would make writing Jasmine specs much more error prone. I'm open to suggestions if anyone has a clever idea for how to make this work without requiring specs to be async or to await the call to expect. But I'm going to go ahead and close this as it's not something that we are likely to implement.

Hey, @sgravrock! Thanks for your answer!
After reading all your points above, I came up with an idea. Please, tell me if it could work (and again, forgive me if this is too naive =) ).
First of all, we would need to borrow the idea of cancelable promises described on React's Blog and alter it a bit:
function makeCancelablePromise(originalPromise) {
  let resolved = false;
  let hasCanceled = false;

  const wrappedPromise = new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
    originalPromise.then(val => {
      resolved = true;
      (hasCanceled ? reject({ isCanceled: true }) : resolve(val))
    });
    originalPromise.catch(error => {
      resolved = true;
      (hasCanceled ? reject({ isCanceled: true }) : reject(error))
    });
  });

  return {
    promise: wrappedPromise,
    cancel() {
      hasCanceled = true;
    },
    isResolved() {
      return resolved;
    },
  };
}
Ok. Now, the goal is to use expect with async functions without needing to use await before it:
// `It`'s callback wouldn't need to be async here
it('throws an error on invalid argument', () => {
  expect(async () => {
    await methodBeingTested(invalidArgument);
  }).toThrow(ExpectedError);
});
The rough idea I came up with goes like this:
function expect(param, ...) {

  // ...

  if (isPromise(param)) {
      const cancelablePromise = makeCancelablePromise(promise);

      // We will need this to make the parent it wait for all
      // async expects before exiting
      parentIt.registerAsyncExpect(cancelablePromise.promise);

      // This will let us abort async expects after the
      // specified timeout
      const timeoutId = setTimeout(() => {
          if (!cancelablePromise.isResolved()) {
            cancelablePromise.cancel();

            // Fails the expect here telling the user that the 
            // promise was not called before the specified timeout
            fail(...);
          }
      }, jasmine.DEFAULT_TIMEOUT_INTERVAL);
  }

  // ...
}

function it(...) {

  // ...

  callTestCallback();

  // Either an async expect will get called or it'll get canceled, so
  // there's no need to track the async expects timeouts
  await Promise.all(this.asyncExpects);

  // ...
}

Where:

parentIt: the it block where expects get called
registerAsyncExpect: a method that would keep track of every async callback passed to expects. In the code above, it is filling the this.asyncExpects array.

One problem to be worked out is how to abort on a first failure. Maybe listening for a first rejection could work. We would also need to keep what matcher should be called and use it inside makeCancelablePromise's wrappedPromise's handlers.

If anyone got here from Google, you can use this:
const myAsyncFunction = async () => { ... }
expectAsync(myAsyncFunction()).toBeRejected()

