What I've usually done when I encounter this situation is either:

Remove the beforeEach and inline all of the setup into each it as you've noticed. This is actually what Jasmine does for all of its tests since it also surfaces when our objects are hard to create.
Turn the beforeEach into a (possibly parameterized) function that you can call inside each it. If you don't really have control over the amount of setup because of a framework or something, you can wrap it in an interface you like.

Your example might look like
describe('component', () => {
  const mock = {
    ex() { return 1; }
  };
  function setupComponent() {
    return new Component(mock);
  };
  it('test 1', () => {
    component = setupComponent();
    expect(component.data).toEqual(1);
  });
  it('test 2', () => {
    spyOn(mock, 'ex').and.returnValue(2);
    component = setupComponent();
    expect(component.data).toEqual(2);
  });
});
What you've suggested might make it easier to hide a code/test smell behind some framework magic, making it harder to detect code that could be made better. Additionally, it sounds rather complex and a bit hard to describe to a user, and so not something we're looking to add to Jasmine at this time.
Hope this helps. Thanks for using Jasmine.

