Chances are that your tests would have always passed prior to 2.9.0, even if the returned promise was rejected or resolved to a different value than expected.
In general, .toEqual tries to determine if two objects represent the same value. That's not really possible with promises because they don't expose any properties (at least not in a way that's either public or portable). Prior to 2.9.0, .toEqual treated any two promises as equal because they had the same constructor and had the same properties. Starting with 2.9.0, .toEqual treats two promises as equal only if they are the same object, i.e. === equality.
It looks like you're trying to assert that the promise returned by object.function() has been resolved to undefined. There isn't a way to do exactly that, but you can assert that it eventually resolves to undefined:
it('should return a promise that resolves to undefined', function() {
   return object.function().then(function (result) {
      expect(result).toBeUndefined();
   });
});

Yeah, I had been changing everything to this as an attempt to fix things:
expect(object.function().then).toBeTruthy();
Thanks for the response, I'll just update the tests.

why does toEqual treat promises as equal only if they're the same object?

Because it's not possible (as far as I know) for toEqual to do the same thing with promises that it does with other objects. Let's set aside the pending and rejected cases for now and say that two promises should be considered equal if they're both resolved to the same value. The comparison logic would look something like this:
// ...
if (isPromise(a) && isPromise(b) {
   return isResolved(a) && isResolved(b) && equals(resolvedValue(a), resolvedValue(b));
}
// ...

The problem is that it's not possible to implement isResolved or resolvedValue. The Promise spec doesn't provide any synchronous API for inspecting the state of the promise, only the async then method. Since toEqual is necessarily synchronous, it can't use those async methods. If you're not convinced, you can prove this to yourself by trying to implement isResolved and resolvedValue. Make sure that they return a boolean and use only features that are documented in the Promise spec.
So that leaves only a few options:

Make matchers asynchronous. This would be a major effort and would require literally every Jasmine spec out there to be rewritten.
Throw an exception if a promise is passed to toEqual.
Treat all promises as equal, as before 2.9.0.
Treat promises as equal if they are the same instance, as in 2.9.0.

Option 1 is out of the question, and I think that option 4 is significantly more useful than 2 or 3.

Customizing the pretty printer is something we've been thinking about for a while, but haven't figured out a good way to do it. Where the pretty printer lives right now makes things a bit tricky, since it needs to output something that is useful both in a console format and in a web page without knowing which context it is running in. Possibly even both at the same time, if you're running in a browser via selenium or something and want to potentially see both versions.
Another workaround you might be able to try for spy argument assertions is checking number of calls and using toEqual for argument checking to get the more descriptive output it provides.
expect(mySpy.calls.count()).toEqual(1);
expect(mySpy.calls.mostRecent().args).toEqual(['foo', {}]);
We would also be happy to review a pull request to allow some sort of custom formatters similar to custom equality testers (tracker story: https://www.pivotaltracker.com/story/show/152892751) or a pretty formatter that knows how to deal with different newlines depending on the environment.
Hope this helps. Thanks for using Jasmine!

