 });

I think I have an alternate use case for this feature (or maybe, it's a feature like it?)
The gist is that sometimes, it's helpful when testing jasmine add-ons to be able to test whether code will generate a test failure.  In large projects, you end up bolting on some additional wrappers and test harnesses and the like and that code usually needs testing too.  You need to be able to write a spec like this:
describe('integrationTestHelper', function() {
    it('fails with jasmine.getEnv().fail if express server cannot start', function() {
        spyOn(integrationTestHelper, 'startServer').and.throwError();
        expect(integrationTestHelper(function() { })).toFailWith({
            pass: false, message: 'Spec aborted, integration environment not ready.'
        });
    });
});

For some custom frameworks I've worked on, I've seen copied and pasted a matcher to provide this functionality... the important guts are (cringe):
compare: function (actual, expectedResult) {
  var testResults = [];
  var originalAddExpectationResult = jasmine.Spec.prototype.addExpectationResult;
  jasmine.Spec.prototype.addExpectationResult = function (...result) {
      testResults.push(result);
  };

  actual();

  jasmine.Spec.prototype.addExpectationResult = originalAddExpectationResult;

  if (jasmine.matchersUtil.equals(testResults, expectedResults)) {
      // ....
  }
}

I wonder if something similar could be provided by Jasmine, without the scary prototype monkey patch.

@elliot-nelson this seems like a different use case than the original poster had in mind. I think if you're writing a custom matcher for Jasmine, I would test it by call the compare function on the matcher directly and inspecting the output. This is what Jasmine itself does to test its own matchers and doesn't require any scary code clobbering.
Ultimately, I think that exposing the pass status out to the spec currently being run is more likely to encourage poor usage and hard to debug false positives, than the converse. In general, Jasmine prefers to prevent false positives. The failure mode I'm particularly looking at is a spec where an expectation fails that shouldn't, but because you're checking the outcome and entering a different branch of your test, the test reports as passing when it should be failing.
Hope this helps.

