Clock.js also uses Array.prototype.



      jasmine/src/core/Clock.js


         Line 168
      in
      74287c5







           return Array.prototype.slice.call(argsObj, n); 





Even if the const Function_prototype = Function.prototype; is applied, using spyOn(window, 'Array'); would make jasmine fail again. Trying to capture all possible window Objects like this would be tedious and not a very good practice to be populating the global space or even namespace.

Approach 1
One suggestion here is delegating the prototype property as to the original object. This is:
wrapper.prototype = originalFn.prototype;
This would change:



      jasmine/lib/jasmine-core/jasmine.js


        Lines 5649 to 5655
      in
      12f56fd







           for (var prop in originalFn) { 




             if (prop === 'and' || prop === 'calls') { 




               throw new Error('Jasmine spies would overwrite the \'and\' and \'calls\' properties on the object being spied upon'); 




             } 









             wrapper[prop] = originalFn[prop]; 




           } 





Into:
    for (var prop in originalFn) {
      if (prop === 'and' || prop === 'calls') {
        throw new Error('Jasmine spies would overwrite the \'and\' and \'calls\' properties on the object being spied upon');
      }

      wrapper[prop] = originalFn[prop];
    }
    if (originalFn && originalFn.prototype) {
      wrapper.prototype = originalFn.prototype;
    }

The only drawback I can foresee with this approach is that if we try to prototype something on the spy, we would be actually prototyping it on the original object.

Approach 2
One idea here to avoid this would be only mapping the methods that are required:
    if (!wrapper.prototype) wrapper.prototype = {};
    if (originalFn && originalFn.prototype) {
      wrapper.prototype.apply = originalFn.prototype.apply;
      wrapper.prototype.call = originalFn.prototype.call;
      wrapper.prototype.slice = originalFn.prototype.slice;
      wrapper.prototype.join = originalFn.prototype.join;
    }

This has the advantage of just being a "read" of methods. Adding new prototypes would be destroyed with the wrapper. However, now we are back to the point of continuously having to add all the prototype methods which is not ideal.

Approach 3
The former can also be solved by simply copying the prototype for non-replace methods.
    if (!wrapper.prototype) wrapper.prototype = {};
    if (originalFn && originalFn.prototype) {
      wrapper.prototype = Object.assign(
        originalFn.prototype,
        wrapper.prototype,
      );
    }


